period-2/transatlantic-trade.html.description:
The very existence of transatlantic trade was a huge change, with two major effects - the Columbian exchange and the Atlantic slave tradeThe columbian exchange was an exchange of foods and other species between Afro-Eurasia and the Americas, and was a biological exchange that occurred along with trade and voyages. The impact on Afro-Eurasia was a lot of food and crops that became commonplace - these crops could also grow in Afro-Eurasia, e.g potatoes in Ireland which became extremely commonplace and a huge source of daily calories (cacao is another example that becomes commonplace later.)&nbsp;
There are two key impacts on the Americas: first, the Great Dying, killing of the native populations leaving them ripe for colonization. Second, the importation of cash crops to the Americas led to the colonies becoming profitable and leading to a vicious cycle, and caused the rise of plantations and exploitation of the Americas due to cash crops being able to be grown there well.The slave trade also began with the rise of plantations which demanded cash crops. The plantation structure was created by the Arabs to farm sugar, and was copied by Europeans on any production economy that they colonized and created.
This had a huge change on Africa, which was a major source of slaves - African nations would become funded and financed solely based on the slave trade, and even peaceful nations needed to participate (some exceptions) in order to get access to European arms to defend themselves. This left them high and dry when the Europeans abolished slavery and contributed to the long-term issues in Africa we see today.
